<h1 id="fourier">Fourier</h1><p><br></p><h2 id="frequency-spectra">Frequency Spectra</h2><ul><li>Each 1D signal can be decomposed in a even and odd function and subsequently in a weighted sum  of sines and cosines</li></ul><p><br></p><h2 id="fourier-transform">Fourier Transform</h2><ul><li>Fourier transform stores the magnitude and phase at each frequency</li><li class="ql-indent-1">Magnitude encodes how much signal there is at a particular frequency</li><li class="ql-indent-1">Phase encodes spatial information (indirectly)</li><li class="ql-indent-1">For mathematical convenience, this is often notated in terms of complex numbers</li><li class="ql-indent-2">With R as the real part of the number</li><li class="ql-indent-2">With I as the imaginary part of the number</li></ul><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="428"></p><p>Image taken from Jan van Gemert in 01.3 - Fourier</p><p><br></p><h2 id="spatial-frequency">Spatial frequency</h2><h3 id="what-is-frequency-">What is frequency </h3><ul><li>In Signal processing we had f = c / t so we get cycles per second</li><li>Images do not have a time, it is just a moment record</li><li>We needed something else</li><li>When talking about images/pictures the frequency can be calculated by f = c / m which is gives us cycles per meter</li></ul><p><br></p><h3 id="definition-of-spatial-frequency">Definition of spatial frequency</h3><ul><li>The spatial frequency is the main frequency we use in image processing</li><li>The spatial frequency gives us the cycles per meter from above</li></ul><p><br></p><h3 id="min-and-max-in-spatial-frequencies">Min and max in spatial frequencies</h3><ul><li>For the min we take the longest distance of the image and put one cycle in there.</li><li>For the max we take the shortest distance and put a cycle in there every 2 pixels (1 (white), 1 (black)), count the cycles and divide over the distance</li></ul><p><br></p><h2 id="spatial-distance-d(p,-q)">Spatial Distance D(p, q)</h2><ul><li>The distance between two points calculated over the height pixel difference (h) and the weight pixel difference (w)</li><li>We calculated the Distance <span class="ql-formula"
